title: Turnovers hurt Wittenberg in loss at DePauw
text:
Posted: 5:29 p.m. Saturday, Oct. 10, 2015 Turnovers hurt Wittenberg in loss at DePauw By David Jablonski Staff Writer 
DePauw didn’t turn the ball over and took advantage of four Wittenberg turnovers to beat the No. 20 Tigers 35-30 on Saturday at Blackstock Stadium in Greencastle, Ind. 
Wittenberg (3-2, 2-2) has suffered two North Coast Athletic Conference losses in the same season for the first time since 2005. Both of its losses this season have come in Indiana. Wabash beat the Tigers 42-14 on Sept. 26, ending Wittenberg’s 23-game NCAC winning streak. 
This is also the first time Wittenberg has lost to an NCAC team other than Wabash since losing 27-6 at Wooster in the final game of the 2008 season. DePauw (5-0, 4-0) lost to Wittenberg 52-14, 45-0 and 34-17 in its first three seasons in the league. 
Wittenberg trailed 28-13 in the third quarter but mounted a comeback. Corey Stump caught a 5-yard touchdown pass from Zack Jenkings. Will Gingery then kicked a 27-yard field goal. 
On DePauw’s first play following the field goal, Matt Hunt threw an 83-yard touchdown pass to Andy Hunt. Jenkins scored on a 64-yard run with 3:34 left to cut the deficit to 35-30. 
On its final drive, Wittenberg advanced to the Depauw 28-yard line before stalling with two incomplete passes and a sack. 
Jenkins completed 36 of 52 passes for 396 yards. He threw three interceptions and one touchdown. DePauw returned one interception 34 yards for its first touchdown. 
Stump caught 13 passes for 148 yards. Luke Landis had nine receptions for 115 yards. 
Sean Gary led the rushing attack with 65 yards on 16 carries. Jimmy Dehnke rushed 13 times for 59 yards. 
Matt Hunt completed 18 of 27 passes for 336 yards with three touchdowns and no interceptions. Andy Hunt caught nine passes for 207 yards. More News
